  <shortdesc class="- topic/shortdesc " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="shortdesc:1;24:14">Understanding the current limitations of markdown-validator before
  you write rules saves hours of debugging. Four limitations affect the types
  of rules you can reliably express today.</shortdesc>

  <conbody class="- topic/body  concept/conbody " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="conbody:1;28:12">

    <section id="flat-dom" class="- topic/section " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="section:1;30:28">
      <title class="- topic/title " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="title:2;31:14">Limitation 1: Flat HTML — within-section queries are not reliable</title>
      <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="p:1;32:10">markdown-validator renders Markdown to HTML using the standard
      <codeph class="+ topic/ph pr-d/codeph " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="codeph:1;33:15">markdown</codeph> library. This library produces <b class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="b:1;33:67">flat HTML</b>:
      all headings are direct children of <codeph class="+ topic/ph pr-d/codeph " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="codeph:2;34:51">&lt;body&gt;</codeph>. There are
      no <codeph class="+ topic/ph pr-d/codeph " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="codeph:3;35:18">&lt;section&gt;</codeph> wrappers that group a heading with its
      content.</p>

      <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="p:2;38:10">This means XPath queries that rely on containment — "find a link that is
      inside the Prerequisites section" — will not work as intended. The query
      <codeph class="+ topic/ph pr-d/codeph " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="codeph:4;40:15">.//h2[1]/following-sibling::a</codeph> does not return links
      within the first H2's section; it returns every link anywhere after the
      first H2 in document order.</p>

      <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="p:3;44:10"><b class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="b:2;44:13">What to do instead:</b> Write rules that check element presence and
      order using absolute position (for example, <codeph class="+ topic/ph pr-d/codeph " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="codeph:5;45:59">.//h2[1]</codeph> for
      the first H2), not containment. For sections, count the heading and rely
      on positional predicates.</p>

      <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="p:4;49:10"><b class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="b:3;49:13">Planned fix:</b> A structured-DOM parser mode is planned for v0.4.
      See the <xref href="../../../site/product/roadmap.md" format="dita" class="- topic/xref " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="xref:1;50:79" dita-ot:orig-format="markdown">product roadmap</xref>.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="no-negation" class="- topic/section " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="section:2;53:31">
      <title class="- topic/title " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="title:3;54:14">Limitation 2: No negation operator</title>
      <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="p:5;55:10">There is no <codeph class="+ topic/ph pr-d/codeph " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="codeph:6;55:30">negate</codeph> field or <codeph class="+ topic/ph pr-d/codeph " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="codeph:7;55:63">not</codeph>
      operator. Expressing "the title must NOT contain the word 'guide'" requires
      a workflow-inversion workaround that is difficult to read and error-prone.
      See the absence-check pattern in
      <xref href="c_rule-design-patterns.dita" class="- topic/xref " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="xref:2;59:48">Rule design patterns</xref>.</p>

      <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="p:6;61:10"><b class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="b:4;61:13">Planned fix:</b> A <codeph class="+ topic/ph pr-d/codeph " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="codeph:8;61:40">negate: true</codeph> field on
      <codeph class="+ topic/ph pr-d/codeph " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="codeph:9;62:15">RuleModel</codeph> is planned for v0.3.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="multi-element-equality" class="- topic/section " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="section:3;65:42">
      <title class="- topic/title " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="title:4;66:14">Limitation 3: Multi-element equality checks are usually wrong</title>
      <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="p:7;67:10">When an XPath query returns more than one element and you use
      <codeph class="+ topic/ph pr-d/codeph " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="codeph:10;68:15">"operation": "=="</codeph>, the evaluator requires <b class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="b:5;68:69">every</b>
      element in the result set to equal the expected value. This is almost
      never the intended behavior.</p>

      <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="p:8;72:10"><b class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="b:6;72:13">Example of the problem:</b> A rule targeting
      <codeph class="+ topic/ph pr-d/codeph " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="codeph:11;73:15">".//h2[last()]/preceding-sibling::h2"</codeph> (to find the
      second-to-last H2) returns <i class="+ topic/ph hi-d/i " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="i:1;74:37">all</i> H2s before the last one. Requiring
      all of them to equal "Clean up resources" fails on any document with
      more than two H2s.</p>

      <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="p:9;78:10"><b class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="b:7;78:13">What to do instead:</b> Target the specific element you want by
      position, not by relative relationship. Use
      <codeph class="+ topic/ph pr-d/codeph " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="codeph:12;80:15">".//h2[last()-1]"</codeph> to get the second-to-last H2
      directly.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="nltk-required" class="- topic/section " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="section:4;84:33">
      <title class="- topic/title " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="title:5;85:14">Limitation 4: NLTK language data must be installed separately</title>
      <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="p:10;86:10">Rules that use the <codeph class="+ topic/ph pr-d/codeph " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="codeph:13;86:37">s</codeph> (sentence count) or
      <codeph class="+ topic/ph pr-d/codeph " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="codeph:14;87:15">p&lt;N&gt;</codeph> (part of speech) operators require NLTK
      language corpora that are not included with the pip package. A fresh
      environment will fail with a LookupError on first use of these rules.</p>

      <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="p:11;91:10"><b class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="b:8;91:13">What to do:</b> Include the NLTK download step in your team's
      onboarding instructions and CI pipeline. See
      <xref href="../../user-guide/tasks/t_download-nltk.dita" class="- topic/xref " xtrf="file:/Volumes/Matt_files/Git/mb/markdown-validator/docs-user/rule-creator-guide/concepts/c_known-limitations.dita" xtrc="xref:3;93:64">Download NLTK language data</xref>.</p>
    </section>

  </conbody>
</concept>